
[1]poison

   POISON, n. poiz'n. [L. pus.]

   1. A substance which, when taken into the stomach,mixed with the blood
   or applied to the skin or flesh, proves fatal or deleterious by an
   action not mechanical; venom. The more active and virulent poisons
   destroy life in a short time; others are slow in their operation,
   others produce inflammation without proving fatal. In the application
   of poison, much depends on the quantity.

   2. Any thing infectious, malignant, or noxious to health; as the poison
   of pestilential diseases.

   3. That which taints or destroys moral purity or health; as the poison
   of evil example; the poison of sin.
